From: Kai Niermann <kai.niermann@googlemail.com>
Date: Tue, 19 May 2026 14:30:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] HID++ 2.0: skip flash rewrite when only the active profile
 changes

`ratbag_profile_set_active()` marks the new profile (and the
previously-active one) `dirty = true`, which sends `hidpp20drv_commit()`
through the per-property update loop and then unconditionally calls
`hidpp20_onboard_profiles_commit()` — a ~1KB write_sector dance per
profile, ~20-40 long HID++ packets, with device-side flash latency
totaling ~1.8s of stalled input reports on a G502 HERO.

That's wasteful when nothing in the profile *data* actually changed.
The post-commit pass in `ratbag_device_commit()` already iterates over
profiles and calls `device->driver->set_active_profile()` for every
profile with `is_active_dirty && is_active`; the HID++ 2.0 driver's
implementation (`hidpp20drv_set_current_profile`) calls feature 0x8100
sub-command 0x30 — a single ~3-5ms HID++ short message that does what
we actually want: flip the firmware's "current profile" pointer
without touching flash.

Two minimal changes:

  - libratbag.c: decouple `is_active_dirty` from `dirty`. An
    active-flag flip alone no longer marks the profile dirty; the
    post-commit `set_active_profile` callback still fires because
    it's gated on `is_active_dirty`, not `dirty`.

  - driver-hidpp20.c: gate the expensive
    `hidpp20_onboard_profiles_commit()` (and the related
    `set_current_dpi_index` follow-up) on whether the per-property
    loop actually wrote anything. If every profile was skipped via
    `if (!profile->dirty) continue`, skip the flash rewrite entirely.

End-to-end on a G502 HERO this drops the HID++ traffic for an active-
profile switch (both profiles already materialised on hardware) from
~30-50 long packets + flash erase to zero — the input report endpoint
no longer stalls. Wall-clock latency in benchmarks drops from ~1875ms
to ~200ms; the residual ~200ms is in sd-event/dbus-broker scheduling
and doesn't involve the device at all, so input reporting is
unaffected.

Profile edits (DPI, button, LED writes) keep the exact same code path
and the same flash-write cost — they actually need it.

Signed-off-by: Kai Niermann <kai.niermann@googlemail.com>
---
diff --git a/src/driver-hidpp20.c b/src/driver-hidpp20.c
--- a/src/driver-hidpp20.c
+++ b/src/driver-hidpp20.c
@@ -1480,10 +1487,18 @@
 	struct ratbag_led *led;
 	struct ratbag_resolution *resolution;
 	int rc;
+	/* Track whether any profile actually had content (DPI / button /
+	 * LED / report-rate) changes. If not — i.e. the only thing dirty
+	 * is the active-profile pointer — skip the expensive flash
+	 * rewrite below. The cheap pointer flip is handled by the
+	 * post-commit pass in ratbag_device_commit() via the
+	 * set_active_profile driver hook. */
+	bool any_profile_data_dirty = false;
 
 	list_for_each(profile, &device->profiles, link) {
 		if (!profile->dirty)
 			continue;
+		any_profile_data_dirty = true;
 
 		if (profile->rate_dirty) {
 			rc = hidpp20drv_update_report_rate(profile, profile->hz);
@@ -1530,19 +1545,29 @@
 		list_for_each(profile, &device->profiles, link)
 			drv_data->profiles->profiles[profile->index].enabled = profile->is_enabled;
 
-		rc = hidpp20_onboard_profiles_commit(drv_data->dev,
-						     drv_data->profiles);
-		if (rc) {
-			log_error(device->ratbag, "hidpp20: failed to commit profile (%d)\n", rc);
-			return RATBAG_ERROR_DEVICE;
-		}
+		/* Only push the on-board profile blob (and the follow-up
+		 * set_current_dpi_index) when something in the data
+		 * actually changed. A pure active-profile flip leaves
+		 * every profile->dirty = false; doing the full flash
+		 * dance in that case is ~1.8s of HID++ traffic for zero
+		 * functional change. The cheap "switch which profile
+		 * is current" call happens in ratbag_device_commit()'s
+		 * post-commit pass via set_active_profile. */
+		if (any_profile_data_dirty) {
+			rc = hidpp20_onboard_profiles_commit(drv_data->dev,
+							     drv_data->profiles);
+			if (rc) {
+				log_error(device->ratbag, "hidpp20: failed to commit profile (%d)\n", rc);
+				return RATBAG_ERROR_DEVICE;
+			}
 
-		list_for_each(profile, &device->profiles, link) {
-			if (profile->is_active) {
-				ratbag_profile_for_each_resolution(profile, resolution) {
-					if (resolution->is_active)
-						hidpp20_onboard_profiles_set_current_dpi_index(drv_data->dev,
-											       resolution->index);
+			list_for_each(profile, &device->profiles, link) {
+				if (profile->is_active) {
+					ratbag_profile_for_each_resolution(profile, resolution) {
+						if (resolution->is_active)
+							hidpp20_onboard_profiles_set_current_dpi_index(drv_data->dev,
+												       resolution->index);
+					}
 				}
 			}
 		}
diff --git a/src/libratbag.c b/src/libratbag.c
--- a/src/libratbag.c
+++ b/src/libratbag.c
@@ -920,13 +920,20 @@
 		if (p->is_active) {
 			p->is_active = false;
 			p->is_active_dirty = true;
-			p->dirty = true;
 		}
 	}
 
 	profile->is_active = true;
 	profile->is_active_dirty = true;
-	profile->dirty = true;
+	/* Deliberately don't flip profile->dirty here. An active-flag
+	 * change alone doesn't require rewriting the profile's data to
+	 * hardware — the post-commit pass in ratbag_device_commit()
+	 * calls device->driver->set_active_profile() for every profile
+	 * with is_active_dirty && is_active, which is the cheap path
+	 * (one HID++ short message on HID++ 2.0). The expensive flash
+	 * rewrite stays gated on real dirty bits set by actual data
+	 * mutations (set_dpi, set_button_mapping, set_led_color, ...).
+	 */
 	return RATBAG_SUCCESS;
 }
 
